00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:12.479
hurdles. But what was something maybe that kind of blindsided you in the position that you're in?

00:22:13.359 --> 00:22:20.560
Yeah. Yeah, totally. I think this is this definitely got to me. So I spoke before about

00:22:21.359 --> 00:22:28.160
like just how big the bank is and how much data work goes on. And this had an effect which I

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:35.839
wasn't quite prepared for, but my colleagues were very good in preparing me for. It was because

00:22:35.839 --> 00:22:43.199
part of this data consulting work that we do, we have a kind of a set of practices that we adopt,

00:22:43.760 --> 00:22:51.599
which is that we have to upskill the business area to maintain their own tooling. So if they

00:22:51.599 --> 00:22:56.560
develop a process, they have to be responsible for maintaining it. And I came from a different

00:22:56.560 --> 00:23:02.319
job where it was like the data scientists would build and maintain the tools. And I'm a maintainer

00:23:02.319 --> 00:23:10.640
at heart. I maintain a bunch of our internal R packages. But my boss had to have a serious

00:23:10.640 --> 00:23:15.520
word with me as he does with like everybody who says, no, no, no, we can't maintain it.

00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:22.959
And that's because if we ever did, we would so quickly become overwhelmed with that maintenance

00:23:22.959 --> 00:23:27.520
burden that we wouldn't be able to do anything else. We wouldn't be able to do anything new.

00:23:29.439 --> 00:23:37.680
And this is very symptomatic of just having a very big organization. And I was totally not

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:45.280
prepared for this. And so, but I wholeheartedly now am on board with that. And I think that just

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:51.359
speaks to, you've got to understand your organization, your organization's needs,

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:59.520
and it might not be the same. So yeah, to perform well in different organizations often means some

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:05.280
things, even sometimes if that means stepping back and saying, actually, I need to coach somebody

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:12.160
through this. I can't just do it myself. And so that was a big one for me.

00:24:13.199 --> 00:24:17.520
Yeah. Thank you so much for that. There's so much packing that, by the way, from a project

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:22.959
management perspective and scope creep, right? Because we, I don't know about you guys, but I

00:24:22.959 --> 00:24:26.880
can tell you from the handful of people I have interacted with on this call, you guys are a

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:33.040
bunch of fixers, right? So we don't like to leave things unhandled or kind of straggling. So we want

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:37.680
to fix things. And I think maintenance is a huge part of that. And so kind of drawing clear cut

00:24:37.680 --> 00:24:42.000
boundaries is something huge for a lot of us. So anyway, thanks for sharing. Appreciate your time.

00:24:42.959 --> 00:24:45.359
My pleasure. Tyler, I see you had a

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:50.479
question in the chat a bit earlier. Do you want to jump in here next?

00:24:51.199 --> 00:24:55.439
Yeah, no. Thank you, James. I love the insights, really helpful, especially from the community

00:24:55.439 --> 00:24:58.719
here. Nice to meet you all. I think one of the things that struck me most with your thousand

00:24:58.719 --> 00:25:04.800
users, I wouldn't say I'm jealous, but as we've rolled out Posit and some of the platforms,

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:10.959
we're ever in this struggle to get new users to adopt successfully and happily to a new platform.

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:14.959
We love the things we love about Posit. It's a little bit more language agnostic. It's a little

00:25:14.959 --> 00:25:20.239
bit more open in that sense and a little bit more flexible to the communities that we're trying to

00:25:20.239 --> 00:25:25.280
serve in analytics and data science, right? But I'm just curious, how do you guys handle that

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:32.239
conversion? Do you mandate training? How do you support those new users? We're forever trying to

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:39.599
make the Emacs peoples happy. How do we really in this space develop the kind of onboarding

00:25:39.599 --> 00:25:45.599
that can lead to what you have demonstrated is a very successful kind of adoption that's a little

00:25:45.599 --> 00:25:49.280
less top-down and like, here's a new platform, everybody on. We're just taking all the old stuff

00:25:49.280 --> 00:25:54.000
away, but more where you can get people to come and really excel and grow.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:26:00.000
Yeah, and the answer is that there are no easy answers. So, a lot of the things that you've

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:05.599
touched on, we do have dedicated training and dedicated trainers and we have a schedule and

00:26:06.479 --> 00:26:10.560
we have excellent people in charge of training who forward that on to us.

00:26:11.359 --> 00:26:16.400
Documentation, also important together with that, the kind of offline asynchronous

00:26:17.359 --> 00:26:25.680
resource that people can consult. I will also say about documentation in general,

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:31.760
writing is a delicate art. So, I think one of the things that makes a difference to me is

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:39.839
actually being given time to write something properly and so to give the user a beginning

00:26:39.839 --> 00:26:46.319
to end experience that is reproducible for them, that is underrated in my experience. So,

00:26:46.319 --> 00:26:51.920
whenever I do sometimes read documentation, sometimes even my own, which is not well written

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:58.560
and it wasn't because the person writing it is bad, it's just because writing is hard and writing

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:03.119
in a way that is clear and concise to the broadest range of people is an underrated skill that we

00:27:03.680 --> 00:27:10.319
are absolutely should dedicate time to. The third pillar of that is just solving

00:27:10.319 --> 00:27:18.640
common problems as much as possible. So, the holy grail of package rollouts or

00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:27.520
rollouts as platform rollouts rather is just the one liner, just can I solve this in one line?

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:32.800
Is this like a one line thing that I can put in and I can get the experience? And we know that,

00:27:33.040 --> 00:27:39.359
everybody on this call will know that it's never as easy as that. So, if you read like some GitHub

00:27:39.359 --> 00:27:47.520
read me's and the read me is two pages long and requires some Linux dependencies and

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:56.560
happens to works on my machine syndrome and as much as you can get away from that is best.

00:27:56.560 --> 00:28:04.079
We do that. I do that. I tried to do that by just my particular solution where I'm good at

00:28:04.079 --> 00:28:09.839
is just to build our packages around it. So, we have a range of our packages at the bank,

00:28:09.839 --> 00:28:15.119
which are specifically for data access. So, we have X system and this system has a way of

00:28:15.119 --> 00:28:22.479
interacting with that particular data. If it's a database or an API or something more bespoke,

00:28:22.479 --> 00:28:29.680
just try and get it one line. I just want one command that I can run and it gets the user from

00:28:30.479 --> 00:28:41.599
zero to connected. And as much of that as you can give to users, the better. Yeah. Never the easiest

00:28:41.599 --> 00:28:50.560
thing, but as much as you can do, you'll reap the benefits. Thank you. I see a big discussion

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:54.640
happening in the chat under one of Mike's questions. So, I'm going to come back to that,

00:28:54.640 --> 00:29:01.680
but there was a Slido question that someone asked anonymously and it was, how does the bank manage

00:29:01.680 --> 00:29:07.359
reproducibility of analysis? I guess this kind of touches on what you were just talking about,

00:29:07.359 --> 00:29:11.760
but especially with the thousand users with varying levels of proficiency.

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:19.359
Yeah, totally. So, I think it's again, some training goes into this. I really think that

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:27.920
Posit's tool set actually do this incredibly well. So, the reason that R Markdown doesn't

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:36.719
really have... You can't just reproduce tiny bits of R Markdown. It's really meant to be start to

00:29:36.719 --> 00:29:43.040
finish, which basically means... This is something I didn't realize until after many years of using

00:29:43.040 --> 00:29:48.800
it. It's reproducible by default and you actually have to opt into the non-reproducible bits.

00:29:49.359 --> 00:29:57.839
And the same thing with Posit Connect and some others, that element is really good.

00:29:59.199 --> 00:30:04.319
But otherwise, it's just the usual sorts of things that people on this call will know about,

00:30:04.319 --> 00:30:10.959
which is try and make examples reproducible, for example, in the reprex package, a lot about

00:30:10.959 --> 00:30:17.040
culture and just running things. But also works in combination with what I just said, which is

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:22.319
it's easier if they have easy data connections, right? So, if you're able to give some people a

00:30:22.319 --> 00:30:26.800
data connection package, then they can do it start to finish. And I think a lot of users

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:32.000
are actually quite good at... A lot of users in my experience are quite good at spotting,

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:37.760
oh, now I can run this M2M because I've got this data connection. I'm not working with extracts.

00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:43.359
And I think that, yeah, tooling is a big part of that.

00:30:43.839 --> 00:30:48.959
Thank you. Mike, for the question and discussion that's happening in the chat,

00:30:48.959 --> 00:30:54.239
do you mind jumping in to kind of summarize the point for me? I was trying to multitask

00:30:54.239 --> 00:30:58.560
and figure out what it was and it was too hard. Yeah, that's kind of exploded. Sorry about that.

00:30:58.560 --> 00:31:06.400
So, this is coming back to James's point that when you develop stuff, you definitely don't want to

00:31:06.400 --> 00:31:16.079
own that solution forever or maintain it because then that... It's like if you develop an R package

00:31:16.959 --> 00:31:23.280
and you put it on to CRAN, you are forever the person who's going to have to live with

00:31:23.920 --> 00:31:33.599
updating that forever. Similarly, within the business I'm in, we have a kind of policy that

00:31:33.599 --> 00:31:37.599
I think is similar to what James was saying, where if we're developing something, it's worth

00:31:37.599 --> 00:31:45.520
the time to develop it in a way that the people we hand it off to can maintain it themselves.

00:31:47.359 --> 00:31:53.920
Maybe not necessarily expand on it greatly, but if there are bits they tweak, they know where to

00:31:53.920 --> 00:32:01.040
tweak and they can get in there and add a new variable or change something from A to B quite

00:32:01.040 --> 00:32:09.680
readily. I'm trying to get away from sometimes what I see, which is if someone comes to you with

00:32:09.680 --> 00:32:14.400
a problem, you solve that problem and you get it out the door as fast as possible and it is what

00:32:14.400 --> 00:32:20.000
it is, you just deliver it and say, well, I'm done here. Typically, if you rush at it, then it's

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:26.800
harder for you and for anyone else to maintain in the long term. So, if you take a little bit longer

00:32:26.800 --> 00:32:32.400
and give them the right solution that's easy for everyone to maintain going forward, it relieves

00:32:32.400 --> 00:32:40.719
the burden on everyone. I think that's what I'm trying to say. I can't help but 100% endorse all

00:32:40.719 --> 00:32:47.119
of that. I only have an example to add, which is I think these can be straightforward things

00:32:47.119 --> 00:32:54.800
like function names. So, just take time to name your functions. It's weird because it feels like

00:32:55.520 --> 00:33:03.280
make work, but it's not, actually. It's just naming functions and naming variables and stuff

00:33:03.280 --> 00:33:09.199
is just a really important part of someone else understanding it in the future and then being able

00:33:09.199 --> 00:33:15.119
to audit it or debug it in the future. But, yeah, 100% endorse.

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:22.880
And, sorry, to kind of expand on that, another example is in like markdown documents or reports

00:33:22.880 --> 00:33:28.560
that you construct for someone, if you make them parameterized and what you do is that you feed in,

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:33.920
if you ingest like a YAML file or something that drives that parameterization,

00:33:34.479 --> 00:33:38.800
then they can always expand it and add future parameters and do all kinds of clever things with

00:33:38.800 --> 00:33:44.560
it. But it then means that you're not kind of locked into a given structure.

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:45.359
Yeah, 100%.

