Yeah, so everything I've kind of said also applies to dashboards. So dashboard design

00:34:29.439 --> 00:34:37.040
is just also a hugely underrated skill and takes time and experience to appreciate

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:47.760
like when a good dashboard is made well. I have the same quandary, which is I try

00:34:48.639 --> 00:35:00.080
and say to managers or whomever I'm trying to convince is it's much more preferable to have a

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:07.120
smaller number of insights conveyed well and continuously than to have a great wedge of

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:15.600
insights to, you know, sort of haphazardly bandied together. The reason that's not always

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:21.600
easy is there's always somebody who wants their favorite chart. And that's where you kind of get

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:27.919
this dashboard fatigue phenomenon where everybody wants to put their own like bit on the Christmas

00:35:27.919 --> 00:35:35.120
tree and eventually the Christmas tree doesn't look good or falls over. And that's a hard thing.

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:40.560
And I think just, yeah, manager gumption to say that actually, we don't do this. We aren't going

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:47.600
to support like every chart. We're not going to support like the broadest range of

00:35:47.600 --> 00:35:54.000
possible visualizations for this thing. We want to focus on core insights and things that

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:00.080
the average person is trying to learn or the average person is going to want to know out of your

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:05.760
output, whether it's a dashboard or whether that's something else.

